WEBVTT

00:05.040 --> 00:06.440
(ENGINE REVVING)

00:06.520 --> 00:08.520
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLASTS)

01:01.360 --> 01:03.840
JEREMY: Look at that.
That is a sturdy car,
that is.

01:03.920 --> 01:06.920
JAMES: Isn't that
a very popular car
with the gay community?

01:07.000 --> 01:08.360
JEREMY: Is it?

01:08.440 --> 01:10.000
JAMES: It's Hammond.
JEREMY: That is Hammond.

01:10.080 --> 01:14.000
-Is that your car?
-Yes, this is my car.

01:14.080 --> 01:15.360
Why is your car there?

01:15.440 --> 01:17.280
Because that's where
the boat dropped me off?

01:17.360 --> 01:18.840
They got to here,
wrapped it in polythene,

01:18.920 --> 01:21.280
lobbed it over the side,
me with it.
That's how they do it.

01:21.400 --> 01:23.160
What's it say on that?
"Global Auto"?

01:23.200 --> 01:24.560
Yeah, GAK.

01:24.680 --> 01:26.480
That's what they said
was the company.

01:28.000 --> 01:29.760
JAMES: I bought it from
an English family

01:29.840 --> 01:32.880
-who had bought a house
in Tuscany.
-Tony Blair.

01:32.960 --> 01:34.760
-Cherie Blair.
-Sting.

01:34.840 --> 01:38.360
Every single lightweight
socialist in Britain

01:38.440 --> 01:41.280
has been in this car.

01:41.360 --> 01:42.960
We're now
leaving Cartagena

01:43.040 --> 01:48.240
in our quest to find
many interesting animals
to photograph.

01:48.320 --> 01:51.560
Well, shrimping
and forest products
obviously, er...pays well.

01:51.640 --> 01:54.240
-Look at the boats out there.
JAMES: I know,
that is amazing, isn't it?

01:54.320 --> 01:56.880
You often see that. The
most humble of commodities

01:56.960 --> 01:59.760
and it yields
just incredible wealth.

01:59.840 --> 02:01.840
-Ooh!
-(SCREECHING)

02:03.560 --> 02:06.240
-(ENGINE CLATTERS)
-Argh!
-Turn it off!

02:06.320 --> 02:10.520
JEREMY: It is one of the most
stupid pieces of engineering
ever, that truck.

02:12.520 --> 02:15.040
Right, Jaguars, they are
very difficult to spot

02:15.120 --> 02:17.880
and very, very rare.

02:18.000 --> 02:19.760
This is proper jungle now.

02:19.840 --> 02:22.600
-(CLUNKS)
-Oh, dear.

02:22.720 --> 02:24.440
I think I've just
lost the exhaust pipe.

02:26.440 --> 02:28.080
JEREMY:
What are we going to do?

02:28.160 --> 02:32.000
People could
come out here for 40 years
and not see a jaguar.

02:32.080 --> 02:34.080
RICHARD: Well, we could
use my trap cameras.

02:35.520 --> 02:37.880
-He parked his car there.
-Yes.

02:38.000 --> 02:39.960
-Turn it round.
-Oh, that'll mess
with his head.

02:40.040 --> 02:42.160
So he comes down
in the morning.
Imagine his face.

02:42.240 --> 02:43.440
He'll think he's gone mad.

02:43.520 --> 02:46.520
One, two, three. Move it.

02:46.600 --> 02:47.960
One, two...

02:48.040 --> 02:50.360
Did we get any pictures?

02:50.440 --> 02:53.400
-Right. Ah, look, there!
-That's it!

02:53.480 --> 02:54.680
There's his head,
there's his head.

02:54.760 --> 02:56.520
That's the ace of spades,
the jaguar.

02:56.600 --> 02:58.640
That's Saddam Hussein.

02:58.720 --> 03:03.080
We've now gotta
go and get his sons,
Uday... and the other one.

03:03.160 --> 03:05.080
What was
his other son called?

03:05.160 --> 03:06.360
Edgar.

03:09.080 --> 03:10.600
JEREMY:
With the jaguar in the bag,

03:10.680 --> 03:13.520
our sights were set
on the next target,

03:13.600 --> 03:15.560
another rare and
reclusive creature.

03:16.640 --> 03:18.640
The spectacled bear.

03:19.960 --> 03:22.840
We now have to drive
200 miles

03:22.920 --> 03:24.520
to find the sort of terrain

03:24.600 --> 03:28.160
where we're gonna be
able to photograph

03:28.240 --> 03:31.480
the king of spades,
Edgar Hussein.

03:31.560 --> 03:32.840
Paddington.

03:34.800 --> 03:38.720
To help pass the time,
entertainment was
provided by James,

03:38.800 --> 03:42.440
trying to overtake trucks
in his one-litre Panda.

03:43.880 --> 03:46.880
Right. No.

03:46.960 --> 03:50.560
He can't see past them
cos his steering wheel's
on the correct side.

03:50.640 --> 03:53.240
JAMES: Cor, bloody hellfire.

03:53.320 --> 03:55.040
So he has to
lunge out of the...
(LAUGHS)

03:55.120 --> 04:00.280
..and then there's this
ridiculously roarty noise
as he sets off.

04:00.360 --> 04:02.560
(ENGINE ROARS)

04:02.640 --> 04:04.400
Holy crap! Come on, car.

04:06.640 --> 04:08.840
(LAUGHS)

04:08.920 --> 04:11.600
Oh, my God!

04:11.680 --> 04:15.320
Oh-ho, I enjoyed
watching that one.

04:15.400 --> 04:18.320
Right, blokes,
I can't keep this
lorry-overtaking up all day.

04:18.400 --> 04:21.560
-My ring piece
is gonna be in tatters.
-(LAUGHS)

04:23.160 --> 04:25.200
What is wrong
with this bloke?

04:25.240 --> 04:29.120
JEREMY: I don't know
what he's been taking,
but he's all over the shop.

04:29.200 --> 04:31.560
He's had a lot of shrimp.
The man's a... an idiot.

04:31.640 --> 04:35.120
(LAUGHS)

04:35.200 --> 04:40.920
JEREMY: As the day wore on,
the Trump truck proved to be
its usual, reliable self.

04:41.000 --> 04:42.480
(HISSING)

04:42.560 --> 04:44.160
RICHARD: Oh, dear.

04:44.240 --> 04:45.520
Oh, dear.

04:45.600 --> 04:47.360
That's not good.

04:47.480 --> 04:49.480
That is bad.

04:50.760 --> 04:52.800
Oh, no.

04:52.920 --> 04:56.640
Oh, God.

04:56.720 --> 05:01.360
Just had a message
asking if I'd like to go back
and help Mr Hammond,

05:01.480 --> 05:04.920
er, mend his monster truck.

05:05.000 --> 05:07.000
Let me think about that.

05:08.480 --> 05:09.760
No, I wouldn't.

05:11.520 --> 05:13.320
Out you come.

05:13.360 --> 05:15.680
Air-conditioning radiator.

05:15.760 --> 05:17.080
Useless.

05:17.160 --> 05:19.520
Still, could be worse.

05:19.600 --> 05:21.600
Could be him over there.

05:21.680 --> 05:22.800
Yeah.

05:22.880 --> 05:25.800
My guess is his brakes
have failed

05:25.880 --> 05:28.640
and he's hooked a wheel
over there to stop it
rolling back.

05:31.200 --> 05:33.200
Er, is this you?

05:34.240 --> 05:35.320
You?

05:35.400 --> 05:37.400
(MAN SPEAKS LOCAL LANGUAGE)

05:39.000 --> 05:41.000
Er, yeah, that, what he said.

05:46.320 --> 05:47.600
Huh?

05:47.680 --> 05:49.400
OK.

05:49.480 --> 05:51.480
-Gracias.
-(MAN SPEAKS LOCAL LANGUAGE)

05:54.120 --> 05:58.200
JEREMY: Eventually
the world's greatest linguist
got his truck going...

06:00.960 --> 06:02.960
and caught us up.

06:07.680 --> 06:13.240
And the next morning
we all woke in the pretty
hill town of Villa de Leyva.

06:13.320 --> 06:15.320
(BELL RINGS)

06:29.240 --> 06:31.720
Why have you done this
to all my trousers?

06:31.800 --> 06:33.840
You said you were hot.

06:33.920 --> 06:35.400
Well, I am now.

06:35.480 --> 06:37.360
(BELL CONTINUES TO RING)

06:46.800 --> 06:50.120
It's a Sunday morning in
a Spanish-speaking country.

06:50.200 --> 06:52.440
It's 8:15 am.

06:52.520 --> 06:55.520
Chances of a trouser shop
being open...?

06:55.600 --> 06:57.280
Nil.

06:57.360 --> 06:58.480
Jeremy.

06:58.560 --> 07:00.600
-Morning.
-How you doing?

07:00.680 --> 07:02.560
Very good.
Sorry, that's not...

07:02.640 --> 07:06.040
James and Richard
cut my trousers up.

07:06.120 --> 07:08.760
Why do I have to be
recognised here,
for God's sake?

07:11.120 --> 07:15.480
Once I'd sorted the trouser
crisis, we continued onwards.

07:17.360 --> 07:19.360
â™ª LOS YETIS: Me Siento Loco

07:33.320 --> 07:37.560
JEREMY:
And eventually we arrived
in spectacled bear country.

07:40.440 --> 07:41.920
Right, now, listen.

07:42.000 --> 07:44.120
RICHARD: Erm...
JAMES: Ho-ho-ho-ho.
-There's a lot to do.

07:44.200 --> 07:45.840
-What?
-I don't like your trousers.

07:45.920 --> 07:47.880
Well, no,
at least he's trying.
He's making an effort.

07:47.960 --> 07:49.320
You should have
gone the whole hog.

07:49.400 --> 07:50.800
Maybe some nice...
Hey, we're out--

07:50.880 --> 07:52.680
We're in the
outdoors, some nice chaps.

07:52.760 --> 07:54.960
Suede,
but ventilated at the back.

07:55.040 --> 07:57.280
And that shirt.
You've picked up that colour.

07:57.360 --> 07:59.000
Have you been getting advice?

07:59.080 --> 08:01.440
May we turn our attention to
the bears now, to Paddington?

08:01.520 --> 08:02.960
Your skin's flaking.

08:03.040 --> 08:05.080
-You should moisturise.
-It's... What?

08:05.160 --> 08:06.920
-You should moisturise.
-You should moisturise
a little bit.

08:07.000 --> 08:08.800
-Why should I moisturise?
-Because
your skin's flaking off.

08:08.880 --> 08:12.160
Because you're dry.
You look like something
found in a pyramid.

08:12.240 --> 08:14.840
Anyway, listen,
we must turn our attention...

08:14.920 --> 08:17.640
-(RICHARD LAUGHS)
-We must turn
our attention...

08:17.720 --> 08:19.040
"Let's have a look
at the sarcophagus.

08:19.120 --> 08:20.800
Argh!"

08:20.880 --> 08:24.600
-"I'm not putting that
in the British Museum."
-(RICHARD GUFFAWS)

08:24.680 --> 08:27.880
Rather than put up with
any more of this persecution,

08:27.960 --> 08:32.560
I insisted we saddle up
and set off
to look for Paddington.

08:34.640 --> 08:36.920
I don't actually know... I've
seen a picture of these bears

08:37.000 --> 08:40.640
but I don't actually know
how big they are. Are they
two feet or ten feet?

08:40.720 --> 08:43.720
I just don't know.

08:43.760 --> 08:46.720
Keep it diagonal, obviously,
while crossing these things.

08:47.840 --> 08:49.520
-(CREAKING)
-Oh, shite!

08:49.640 --> 08:51.280
RICHARD:
Oh-ho!

08:51.360 --> 08:53.880
Oh-ho! Look at you
with a wheel in the air!

08:53.960 --> 08:56.360
Can we please try not to make
this look like it's a problem

08:56.440 --> 08:58.520
cos the ladies and gentlemen
will think we're hopeless.

09:00.400 --> 09:03.240
JEREMY:
I tried to drive myself out.

09:03.320 --> 09:05.280
Which went well.

09:05.360 --> 09:08.360
-Speed and power.
-(LAUGHS) He's just
dug himself a hole!

09:08.440 --> 09:10.520
So I asked Hammond for help.

09:10.600 --> 09:13.120
But, predictably,
his pickup truck

09:13.200 --> 09:16.720
chose that moment to
go into one-wheel drive.

09:19.440 --> 09:21.400
Oh...

09:21.480 --> 09:23.520
Oh, dear.

09:23.600 --> 09:26.760
There was only one solution.

09:26.880 --> 09:28.320
-Could you give me
a tow cos...
-No.

09:28.400 --> 09:30.040
No, I'm very close
to coming out.

09:30.120 --> 09:32.320
-Well, we know that.
You've bought a Jeep.
-Yes, no, that's...

09:32.400 --> 09:34.400
-Oh, I see.
-(LAUGHS)

09:37.520 --> 09:41.520
Every single time
I open my mouth now,
you've got some reference...

09:41.600 --> 09:43.760
No, it's great. It's good.

09:43.880 --> 09:45.880
We're all friends.

09:45.960 --> 09:49.440
With the rope hitched up,
we were ready to go.

09:49.520 --> 09:51.520
So I'll give you a small tug.

09:51.600 --> 09:53.960
-Was that a gentle tug?
-There we go.

09:54.040 --> 09:57.640
And then it's down to you
because I haven't got the
weight to pull you, OK?

09:57.760 --> 09:59.760
Here we go, three, two, one.

10:02.640 --> 10:04.640
-Whoa!
RICHARD: Exciting.

10:06.640 --> 10:08.760
Yes, go on!

10:08.880 --> 10:12.120
-A Fiat Panda!
-Yesssss!
JAMES: Yes!

10:12.200 --> 10:15.200
Jeremy Corbyn just pulled
Freddy Mercury out.

10:15.280 --> 10:17.640
It's a meeting of minds.

10:17.720 --> 10:19.720
(LAUGHS)

10:21.200 --> 10:23.200
I'm not sure we're
very good at fist-bumping.

10:26.640 --> 10:28.760
JEREMY:
With that calamity sorted,

10:28.880 --> 10:33.000
Hammond got
four-wheel drive back
and we resumed our mission.

10:34.640 --> 10:36.880
Right.

10:36.960 --> 10:39.760
Go on a bear hunt.

10:39.840 --> 10:41.520
Soon, however...

10:41.600 --> 10:43.600
(CLANKING)

10:46.240 --> 10:47.960
-(CLANKING CONTINUES)
-Oh, dear.

10:50.520 --> 10:53.120
What's up, Hammond?

10:53.200 --> 10:57.640
RICHARD:
I think something's broken
somewhere in the drive line.

10:57.760 --> 11:00.600
Am I now having to pull
Hammond... Oh, God.

11:00.680 --> 11:04.000
Right, and pull Hammond out.

11:04.080 --> 11:08.680
RICHARD: Once my pickup
had been pulled out...

11:08.760 --> 11:11.520
I quickly found the fault.

11:11.600 --> 11:13.440
Broken the half shaft.

11:13.520 --> 11:15.640
JAMES: Ohhh!

11:15.720 --> 11:17.880
RICHARD: I think this is now
a two-wheel drive.

11:20.360 --> 11:23.360
JEREMY: Still, while there
had been a few mishaps,

11:23.440 --> 11:28.680
our cars were able to
take us comfortably to a
suitable bear-spotting point.

11:35.160 --> 11:38.680
I've got a cool-box in the
back of the Jeep full of
zesty, refreshing drinks.

11:40.200 --> 11:42.560
The temperature's perfect.

11:42.640 --> 11:44.840
I'm not out of breath.
I didn't have to walk here.

11:46.200 --> 11:48.200
However, because
the trap cameras

11:48.280 --> 11:50.160
had been ruined
by the jaguar,

11:50.240 --> 11:54.000
this time
we would need to deploy
our immense patience.

12:02.280 --> 12:04.440
Soon, however...

12:04.520 --> 12:06.200
I'm bored!

12:06.280 --> 12:08.440
-I'm bored!
JAMES: Bored.

12:08.520 --> 12:11.320
Booooooored!

12:14.520 --> 12:18.440
JEREMY: So, to make life
more interesting,
we kept on driving.

12:22.760 --> 12:25.080
Right, we go higher up
the mountain.

12:34.360 --> 12:40.560
This is the absolute
worst terrain
for the Jeep's suspension.

12:40.640 --> 12:44.440
God, I'd like to meet the man
who put these big tyres
on this thing.

12:44.520 --> 12:47.120
And I'd like to strangle him.

12:47.200 --> 12:50.000
Still, could be worse.

12:50.080 --> 12:51.360
-Hole.
-(THUD)

12:53.600 --> 12:56.280
-Oh, dear.
-(LAUGHS)

12:56.360 --> 12:58.560
Looks like Jeremy Corbyn's
struggling a bit there.

12:58.640 --> 13:00.640
(REVVING)

13:02.760 --> 13:05.840
No, somehow he's managed to
get it back on its wheels.

13:13.280 --> 13:15.640
And still it goes!

13:17.360 --> 13:19.200
JAMES: But then...

13:19.280 --> 13:21.520
Oh, God.

13:21.600 --> 13:23.600
Oh, hold on.

13:24.600 --> 13:26.600
Big hole there, chaps.

13:29.160 --> 13:30.840
-Yeah, you see that...
JAMES: Oh-ho-ho.

13:30.920 --> 13:32.560
(RICHARD LAUGHS)

13:32.640 --> 13:34.400
JEREMY: That's not...
What are you on about?

13:34.480 --> 13:36.160
-It's massive!
-That's quite a big hole.

13:36.240 --> 13:39.160
-It just isn't,
though, is it?
-Other than that it is.

13:39.240 --> 13:41.440
-Look at the size of it.
JAMES: Although...
JEREMY: Look.

13:41.520 --> 13:44.520
RICHARD: No, that's...
JEREMY: No, stop
and listen to the expert.

13:44.600 --> 13:46.960
Cut it this way.

13:47.040 --> 13:51.360
Gravity gets you down there
and then you simply
drive up the other side.

13:51.440 --> 13:54.640
Oh, Professor, how do you
work these things out?

13:54.720 --> 13:56.400
-You drive out.
-Look at your tyres.

13:56.480 --> 13:59.240
-Yeah, Hammond,
that's a monster truck.
-Only two are driven.

13:59.320 --> 14:01.240
-It's a monster truck!
-It runs over cars.

14:01.320 --> 14:02.960
I've seen them do it
on the telly.

14:03.040 --> 14:05.120
-And they're two-wheel drive.
-They are, actually. Yes.

14:05.200 --> 14:09.880
They are two-wheel drive
and they... Monster trucks
could easily do that.

14:09.960 --> 14:14.760
With Hammond refusing
point blank to help, James
and I did manual labour,

14:14.840 --> 14:18.080
and cut away the edge
of the bank.

14:18.160 --> 14:20.280
Keep going, chaps, you'll
fill the hole in eventually.

14:20.360 --> 14:22.960
What about that then,
Hammond? That's softened it
up a bit. Fancy that?

14:23.040 --> 14:25.960
It's easy now.
I'll do it in a Lamborghini.

14:26.040 --> 14:28.560
That's got rid of
that big stony bit.

14:28.640 --> 14:30.840
That's roughly where
your wheel's gonna go.

14:30.920 --> 14:32.880
Yeah, just before
the massive drop.

14:32.960 --> 14:36.240
Ever since
your last accident,
you've lost your bottle.

14:36.320 --> 14:38.280
No, it doesn't require
bottle to do that.

14:38.360 --> 14:41.280
It can't be done.
It's not the same.

14:41.360 --> 14:42.880
Well, you're gonna do it.

14:42.960 --> 14:44.320
-No, I'm not.
-You are.

14:44.400 --> 14:46.520
No, I'm not.

14:46.600 --> 14:48.600
Right, here we go.

14:50.600 --> 14:51.880
Gravity will
get you in a minute.

14:51.960 --> 14:54.800
Yes, I know gravity works.
I'm familiar with it.

14:54.880 --> 14:56.960
Just do it and then drive up
the other side.

14:57.040 --> 14:59.040
Hurry up, quicker.

15:01.320 --> 15:02.920
Oh, God!

15:03.000 --> 15:05.520
-There you go.
-Exactly as I said.

15:05.600 --> 15:07.880
Now drive up the other side.

15:07.960 --> 15:09.960
Hold on.

15:36.320 --> 15:38.320
(ENGINE REVVING)

15:49.080 --> 15:51.880
I told you
this wouldn't work.

15:51.960 --> 15:54.360
(ENGINE STOPS)

15:54.440 --> 15:56.280
-I've had an idea.
-What?

15:56.360 --> 15:59.400
-You know that sort of roll
bar thing he's got there.
-Yeah.

15:59.480 --> 16:01.160
If we get the sand ladders
from the support truck

16:01.240 --> 16:04.240
and lay them on that,
we could drive across him.

16:06.600 --> 16:10.320
-Couldn't we?
-Isambard Kingdom May.

16:10.400 --> 16:12.400
Hammond, we've had
a brilliant idea.

16:14.440 --> 16:16.600
I don't know
what they're gonna do.

16:16.680 --> 16:18.680
I just know
it's not gonna work.

16:23.480 --> 16:26.640
(GROANS) This weighs a tonne.

16:28.040 --> 16:29.800
(GRUNTS)

16:29.880 --> 16:32.440
-(THUDS)
-Oh, mind my roof!

16:35.000 --> 16:37.240
It won't reach.

16:37.320 --> 16:39.880
Oh... No... Don't...
Come on...

16:39.960 --> 16:41.960
Ohh...

16:43.040 --> 16:46.360
(ELECTRIC CUTTING)

16:46.440 --> 16:49.640
(MANUAL SAWING)

16:49.720 --> 16:52.360
-(HAMMERING)
JEREMY: Eventually
our magnificent bridge

16:52.440 --> 16:54.080
was complete.

16:59.280 --> 17:02.440
And James volunteered
to cross it first.

17:02.520 --> 17:05.240
JEREMY: Come on, Hammond,
you must be pleased.

17:05.320 --> 17:07.320
No, I'm not pleased!

17:07.400 --> 17:09.000
First heroic thing it's done.

17:09.080 --> 17:10.960
First time
it's not holding us up.

17:11.040 --> 17:13.160
-(GENTLE REVVING)
-Is that looking good?

17:13.240 --> 17:15.560
-Looking good.
-No, it's looking ridiculous.

17:15.680 --> 17:17.680
(REVVING)

17:23.040 --> 17:25.040
(CREAKING)

17:28.280 --> 17:29.520
-It worked.
-Yes!

17:29.560 --> 17:31.800
-How about that?
-Yes!

17:31.920 --> 17:33.480
-Piece of cake.
-Oh, no fist bumping.

17:33.560 --> 17:35.800
-Oh, no, we don't
do that, do we, yeah.
-That hurt.

17:35.880 --> 17:38.040
JEREMY:
Now, though, it was my turn,

17:38.080 --> 17:41.960
in a car that was
more than twice the weight
of the Panda.

17:45.480 --> 17:48.440
Hold on, I can't even see
the sand ra...

17:48.520 --> 17:51.320
I can't see the rail
on this side.

17:51.440 --> 17:56.040
JAMES: Tiny, tiny bit
your left. That's it.
Right, straight.

17:56.080 --> 17:59.560
Tiny, tiny bit to your left,
but really tiny.

17:59.640 --> 18:01.640
That's good.

18:05.760 --> 18:08.320
Right on the edge.

18:08.440 --> 18:09.720
Now very slowly.

18:09.800 --> 18:11.720
Tiny bit of left.

18:11.800 --> 18:14.000
-That's right,
you blithering idiot.
-Right.

18:14.080 --> 18:16.200
Now that is... Oh.

18:16.280 --> 18:17.560
Stop. Stop, stop, stop.

18:17.680 --> 18:19.800
Stop there, stop there.

18:19.920 --> 18:21.320
It's gonna break.

18:21.400 --> 18:22.800
It's not gonna work.

18:22.880 --> 18:24.560
-What?
-It's not gonna work.
-(ENGINE OFF)

18:24.680 --> 18:26.440
Yes, but the thing is
you've stopped me

18:26.520 --> 18:28.400
and there's no other way
of describing it,

18:28.480 --> 18:30.760
-on top of...
-(CREAKING)
-...top of Hammond's car.

18:30.800 --> 18:32.640
Yeah, I know.
Don't jig about too much.

18:32.720 --> 18:34.320
RICHARD: Don't worry about
my truck sitting there.

18:34.400 --> 18:37.560
We're not worried
about your truck!

18:37.640 --> 18:41.560
JAMES: Since Hammond wouldn't
lift a finger, even though
he'd got us into this mess,

18:41.680 --> 18:45.400
I had to get the camera crew
to help beef up
the sand rails.

18:47.800 --> 18:51.080
JEREMY: We're supposed to be
making wildlife photography
look easy and comfortable.

18:51.200 --> 18:54.480
This isn't working.

18:54.560 --> 18:57.560
JAMES: With
the strengthening in place,
it was time to continue.

18:58.560 --> 19:00.560
(ENGINE STARTS)

19:02.560 --> 19:04.560
JAMES: Keep it on that.

19:04.680 --> 19:06.680
Exactly that line.

19:11.560 --> 19:13.320
Yes!

19:13.400 --> 19:14.520
Yeah.

19:14.560 --> 19:16.960
-Right, let's move on.
-Right.

19:21.560 --> 19:23.560
Well, they're across.

19:32.160 --> 19:34.800
-Oh, God.
-Why have you stopped?

19:34.920 --> 19:37.080
You're not gonna
believe this.

19:37.200 --> 19:38.680
What?

19:38.760 --> 19:40.760
There's a river.

19:42.240 --> 19:43.720
Can we go through it?

19:43.800 --> 19:45.800
Not in a million years.

19:57.920 --> 19:59.200
What are you doing?

19:59.280 --> 20:01.440
It's... Just round that
corner there's a river.

20:01.520 --> 20:02.640
-Yeah.
-Blocked.

20:02.720 --> 20:03.960
But you've been gone...

20:04.040 --> 20:05.560
So what was
the point in that?

20:05.680 --> 20:07.520
Well, at least it meant
your car was useful twice.

20:07.560 --> 20:09.000
-It was.
-Well, you ended up
where you...

20:09.080 --> 20:10.720
We've achieved nothing,

20:10.800 --> 20:12.520
apart from ruining my truck
and turning it into a bridge.

20:12.560 --> 20:14.680
Yeah, but we needed to do
that to get back again.

20:14.760 --> 20:17.280
-Exactly.
-But if you hadn't gone...

20:17.320 --> 20:20.440
If you hadn't gone there,
you wouldn't need a bridge
to get back, would you?

20:20.520 --> 20:22.960
JAMES: We didn't know
there was a river there
until we'd gone there.

20:23.040 --> 20:26.880
-And there are no bears.
JEREMY: As this debate
was getting us nowhere,

20:26.960 --> 20:31.080
we pulled an ungrateful
Hammond out of his hole,

20:31.200 --> 20:33.880
and found another route
up the mountain.

20:38.760 --> 20:41.880
I'm actually looking forward
to seeing a bear,
I really am.

20:41.960 --> 20:45.720
I like all bears, except
polar bears, which I hate.

20:45.800 --> 20:48.160
They're vicious and
they eat schoolchildren.

20:49.680 --> 20:52.960
Joyously, we soon found
another suitable spot,

20:53.040 --> 20:55.800
where I discovered
I had a small problem.

20:57.480 --> 21:00.720
I'm still not high enough up
to see over the shrubs.

21:00.800 --> 21:02.280
Well, nothing we can do
about it now.

21:02.320 --> 21:04.080
-What?
-Shut up, nothing you
can do about it.

21:04.200 --> 21:06.400
-I wish I was a bit higher.
-That's how high you are.

21:06.480 --> 21:08.320
(GROANS)

21:08.400 --> 21:10.400
JEREMY: We settled down
to wait.

21:11.440 --> 21:13.480
But shortly...

21:13.560 --> 21:15.560
And inevitably...

21:17.240 --> 21:19.240
-Bored.
-Me too.

21:21.760 --> 21:23.560
It does get boring, this.

21:23.640 --> 21:25.000
It's 20 minutes.

21:25.080 --> 21:27.920
(ANIMAL BARKS)

21:28.000 --> 21:30.320
-What was...what was that?
-That's bear noise.

21:30.440 --> 21:32.560
-Ssh.
-(ANIMAL BARKS)

21:32.640 --> 21:34.800
-I'm not bored now.
-That is a bear.

21:34.920 --> 21:37.240
(GROWLING)

21:37.320 --> 21:39.320
-It's a bear, it's a bear!
-I can't see it.

21:39.400 --> 21:41.320
-It's fantastic.
-It's a bear.

21:44.160 --> 21:46.080
-Yes, it is, it moved.
-Ssh.

21:46.160 --> 21:47.800
-I can see its face.
-Oh, yes.

21:52.800 --> 21:54.520
-I took a picture of a bear!
-Ssh.

21:55.840 --> 21:57.080
(WHISPER)

22:00.040 --> 22:01.760
Why won't it come over here?

22:01.840 --> 22:04.000
Probably because
you're talking.

22:04.080 --> 22:05.640
I think we're a bit
too conspicuous.

22:05.720 --> 22:07.800
-We're scaring them off.
-You are.

22:07.880 --> 22:12.320
Your car and his car,
they're too... bright.

22:12.400 --> 22:14.400
JAMES: I know.

22:18.040 --> 22:22.280
JEREMY: Hammond and May
agreed that my car was
the quietest and most subtle.

22:24.240 --> 22:26.840
So they suggested
I should creep towards

22:26.920 --> 22:30.680
the largest flesh-eating
mammal in all of
South America.

22:35.800 --> 22:39.440
He is coming close range.
Weapon too close
for my big gun.

22:40.560 --> 22:42.640
He is coming!

22:42.720 --> 22:44.720
He is coming.

22:52.800 --> 22:55.720
(BEAR GROWLS AND SNEEZES)

22:55.800 --> 22:58.920
JEREMY:
And then, to top it all...

22:59.000 --> 23:00.440
Bears are shitting
in the woods.

23:00.520 --> 23:02.520
The bear is shitting
in the woods.

23:04.080 --> 23:07.280
I have now seen everything.

23:07.360 --> 23:10.400
Edgar Hussain is done.

23:10.480 --> 23:12.480
(ENGINE STARTS)

23:13.640 --> 23:15.640
King of spades, tick.

