-(RATTLING)
-Ah, now the music's stopped,

34:38.640 --> 34:43.000
I have uncovered a small
problem with my modification.

34:43.080 --> 34:46.480
JAMES: What's that?
-Quite a lot of rattling.

34:46.560 --> 34:48.160
(RATTLING CONTINUES)

34:51.080 --> 34:53.080
(REVVING)

34:53.160 --> 34:56.400
I don't wanna speak too soon,
but I think my big wheels
are working.

34:56.480 --> 35:00.160
The car is going along,
they're not rubbing
on anything.

35:00.280 --> 35:02.280
The ride's still reasonable.

35:02.360 --> 35:04.360
â™ª LOS YETIS:
Llegaron Los Peluqueros

35:07.200 --> 35:12.600
JEREMY: As we left Bogota,
and picked up speed, my mods
became even more annoying.

35:14.640 --> 35:16.960
Sit-rep, and it's not good.

35:17.040 --> 35:21.120
I mean, yes, I can't hear
the rattling from
the scissor lift any more,

35:21.160 --> 35:24.760
but only because
the roof is flapping
like a bastard.

35:24.840 --> 35:28.560
And, steering's
worryingly light,

35:28.640 --> 35:30.320
cos all the weight's
at the back.

35:30.400 --> 35:34.440
Also, the rear tyres now
never catch on the arches.

35:34.520 --> 35:36.520
-(RUBBING)
-Apart from then.

35:36.600 --> 35:38.800
-(RUBBING)
-And then.

35:38.880 --> 35:41.200
(RUBBING)

35:41.320 --> 35:44.160
JAMES: And in the Panda,
things weren't
that great either.

35:45.560 --> 35:47.040
(KNOCKING)

35:47.120 --> 35:49.560
I'm starting to hear some
alarming noises from my car,

35:49.640 --> 35:52.760
-so I thought I'd share them
with you.
-(KNOCKING)

35:52.840 --> 35:56.200
There's one of them.

35:56.320 --> 35:58.360
It's almost as if the wheels
have moved on the hubs

35:58.440 --> 36:00.480
-and are starting to touch
little bits of the arches.
-(KNOCKING)

36:00.560 --> 36:03.160
Can you hear that?

36:03.200 --> 36:08.160
To try and stop the roof
flapping, I've put my monopod
here, to keep it all taut.

36:08.280 --> 36:11.200
-And that hasn't worked.
-(RATTLING)

36:11.320 --> 36:12.960
-Rattling, tyre noise.
-(FLAPPING)

36:13.040 --> 36:14.640
-Flapping.
-(REVVING)

36:14.760 --> 36:16.360
Yeah. Yeah.

36:16.440 --> 36:18.600
Bad.

36:18.640 --> 36:20.640
Still, could be worse.

36:23.320 --> 36:25.480
Oh, cock.

36:25.560 --> 36:26.800
Right, this is quite bad.

36:26.880 --> 36:28.640
What's happened
on all those windy bits,

36:28.680 --> 36:30.560
as the car leans to one side
and the other,

36:30.640 --> 36:34.000
is that the bigger tyre
has rubbed against
the filler pipe,

36:34.080 --> 36:35.920
from the cap here
down to the tank,

36:36.000 --> 36:39.160
and it's made a little hole
in it and the fuel
is gushing out,

36:39.200 --> 36:41.760
which is why I was getting
a bit stoned
as I was driving along.

36:41.840 --> 36:44.880
I thought it was just
altitude, but it was
actually petrol fumes.

36:44.960 --> 36:49.440
So what I'm gonna do is, er,
drain the tank down
by about half,

36:49.520 --> 36:51.520
so the level is below
that bit of the pipe.

36:51.600 --> 36:55.360
I will patch up that hole,
put the fuel back in

36:55.440 --> 36:57.600
and then I'll put
the proper wheels back on.

37:01.520 --> 37:04.200
JEREMY: While May did...
what he just said,

37:04.320 --> 37:07.760
Hammond and I hoovered up
some animal pictures...

37:12.600 --> 37:14.640
-Oh, yeah.
-(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

37:16.520 --> 37:18.360
I got it.

37:18.440 --> 37:23.440
..in terrain that was
becoming absolutely
spectacular.

37:34.520 --> 37:38.400
It's the variety of Colombia
that staggers me most of all.

37:38.480 --> 37:40.480
One minute you're in
what looks like Japan.

37:41.920 --> 37:43.920
Then it's
the Yorkshire Dales.

37:45.000 --> 37:47.400
Then it's Austria.

37:47.480 --> 37:49.960
Then it's California.

37:50.040 --> 37:54.200
It's like the greatest hits
of the world
all in one place.

37:54.320 --> 37:56.880
I mean, Jesus,
look at that now.

38:09.640 --> 38:12.120
Eventually
we were all reunited,

38:12.160 --> 38:17.920
and, at my insistence,
we began the long climb
to 16,000 feet,

38:18.000 --> 38:19.920
where I knew
the condors would be.

38:24.040 --> 38:25.920
I cannot wait to see a condor

38:26.000 --> 38:31.280
because they are one of
the most superb creations
on Earth.

38:31.360 --> 38:34.760
They just are magnificent.

38:34.840 --> 38:39.920
They can stay
at 18,000 feet all day,
maybe flap their arms once.

38:40.000 --> 38:41.680
Once.

38:41.800 --> 38:44.920
Right, gentlemen, we're
passing 10,000 feet now.

38:45.000 --> 38:48.320
Er, how's your
temperature gauges?

38:48.400 --> 38:50.400
Mine's getting hot,
really hot.

38:52.080 --> 38:55.120
JAMES: Er, weirdly,
my car isn't overheating,

38:55.160 --> 38:57.080
but it is producing
some steam

38:57.160 --> 39:00.000
because I think maybe the cap
isn't perfectly sealed

39:00.080 --> 39:02.920
and the ambient pressure
is going down.

39:03.000 --> 39:04.040
Yeah.

39:04.120 --> 39:06.120
Why does he say
ambient pressure?

39:06.160 --> 39:08.080
Why not just pressure?

39:13.760 --> 39:15.440
JEREMY:
Soon we entered the clouds,

39:15.520 --> 39:17.400
and pulled over
to photograph

39:17.480 --> 39:20.120
something else we thought
Amazon might like.

39:22.960 --> 39:24.960
The humming bird.

39:27.800 --> 39:30.760
Sadly, though,
to attract these
wonderful little things,

39:30.840 --> 39:33.200
we had to take
drastic measures.

39:33.320 --> 39:34.640
(THRUMMING)

39:40.680 --> 39:43.040
You know when wildlife
photographers tell you

39:43.120 --> 39:44.760
-how they got the shots?
-Yeah.

39:44.840 --> 39:48.480
I bet they never ever
say, "And then we wore
scarlet lipstick."

39:48.560 --> 39:51.880
RICHARD: No.
-I've never
seen it mentioned.

39:51.960 --> 39:55.480
They also wouldn't say
that if you want the birds
to come up really close,

39:55.560 --> 39:58.680
you need to put a plastic
flower in your mouth.

40:10.800 --> 40:13.440
JAMES: Oh, that one's lovely.
Look at that, look at that.

40:22.880 --> 40:26.000
RICHARD: They are absolutely
beautiful, aren't they?

40:26.080 --> 40:27.320
Shit!

40:27.400 --> 40:29.400
I've gotta get further away.

40:32.800 --> 40:34.800
JAMES: You got it?

40:36.320 --> 40:38.160
JEREMY: Epic.

40:38.280 --> 40:41.440
I've gotta say, of all the
things we've ever done,

40:41.520 --> 40:43.080
that's kind of
up there, really.

40:43.160 --> 40:45.080
-Yeah, it's beautiful.
-I think that might be
my favourite.

40:45.160 --> 40:47.920
And now we've done
one of the world's
smallest birds,

40:48.000 --> 40:52.640
it's time to carry on going
up, and one of the biggest.

40:52.760 --> 40:54.760
-What?
-We've got to get the condor,
haven't we?

40:54.840 --> 40:57.480
-They weren't condors?
-(LAUGHTER)

41:02.760 --> 41:08.200
JAMES: We continued
on Jeremy's journey
up into the heavens.

41:08.320 --> 41:12.840
Right, we're at something
like 11 and a half thousand
feet. We're still climbing.

41:12.920 --> 41:15.560
Car is definitely
struggling now.

41:15.640 --> 41:20.600
The engine burns a mixture
of oxygen and petrol,
mainly oxygen.

41:20.640 --> 41:23.600
The oxygen is going down,
so you can't burn
as much petrol,

41:23.640 --> 41:25.480
so the engine develops
less power.

41:27.440 --> 41:30.160
I'll have to go for second.

41:30.280 --> 41:32.280
Climb, Pepe!

41:33.480 --> 41:35.760
Keeping an eye
on temperature.

41:35.840 --> 41:38.040
It is working extra hard.

41:38.120 --> 41:39.880
It might just pass
a critical level

41:39.960 --> 41:42.400
at which this car can't
suck in enough oxygen

41:42.480 --> 41:45.120
to mix with fuel to burn.

41:45.160 --> 41:49.000
And then
I'll run out of steam.

41:49.080 --> 41:54.160
The good thing
is that while my colleagues
were painting their cars,

41:54.280 --> 41:57.680
I was fitting mine
with oxygen tanks.

41:57.800 --> 41:59.480
So when I start to
really struggle,

41:59.560 --> 42:03.840
I shall simply feed pure O2
to the engine, and me.

42:07.160 --> 42:09.480
JAMES: Oh, my God.

42:09.560 --> 42:11.960
Come on.

42:12.040 --> 42:14.920
Hammond, how are things
in your monster truck?

42:15.000 --> 42:19.160
Not brilliant.
It's gone very wheezy
and it's getting very hot.

42:19.200 --> 42:22.480
We've just passed
14,000 feet now.

42:22.560 --> 42:24.560
Really running out of power.

42:26.160 --> 42:28.480
Switching to oxygen
for the engine.

42:28.560 --> 42:32.320
-(CLICKS)
-There we are, two clicks.

42:32.400 --> 42:34.640
Right, watch this.

42:34.760 --> 42:37.000
(REVVING)

42:37.080 --> 42:39.880
Kick-down is restored.

42:39.960 --> 42:41.840
That's profound,
the difference.

42:41.920 --> 42:44.560
(CACKLES)

42:44.640 --> 42:48.640
Leading
my breathless colleagues,
we continued to climb...

42:51.200 --> 42:55.000
and soon found ourselves
on a volcano.

43:02.200 --> 43:05.520
Last erupted in the 1980s

43:05.600 --> 43:08.080
and killed 25,000 people.

43:09.840 --> 43:13.880
I've never seen anywhere
with fewer animals in it.

43:13.960 --> 43:16.160
Condors live here,
I'm telling you.

43:16.280 --> 43:18.800
They come
and get volcano mice.

43:18.880 --> 43:23.160
You're destroying our cars,
you've got oxygen for you
and your car only,

43:23.280 --> 43:27.320
and we can see nothing!

43:27.400 --> 43:31.600
JEREMY: Hammond
did seem to have a point,
as no condors appeared.

43:33.600 --> 43:37.000
Nothing for it,
we've gotta go higher

43:37.080 --> 43:39.080
to find Colin Condor.

43:40.160 --> 43:42.160
Come on, hurry up, follow me.

43:45.760 --> 43:48.520
This is it,
this is all I've got.

43:48.600 --> 43:54.280
Foot is flat to the floor,
the temperature is flying up.

43:54.360 --> 43:57.120
I've just been told
we're at 15,500 feet.

43:59.720 --> 44:01.720
Oh, God,
not another steep one.

44:08.720 --> 44:10.600
Yes!

44:10.680 --> 44:14.000
JAMES: My plucky
little Panda, however,
was coping rather well.

44:15.480 --> 44:18.440
Oh, ho-ho-ho.

44:18.520 --> 44:20.920
Until it broke down.

44:21.000 --> 44:22.160
(ENGINE GIVES OUT)

44:22.240 --> 44:24.560
Bollocks!

44:24.640 --> 44:27.080
Um, I've got
a completely dead battery.

44:30.040 --> 44:33.280
Right, James, I'm gonna try
and push-start you with this.

44:33.360 --> 44:34.920
I'll be gentle.

44:35.000 --> 44:38.120
OK, please push me with
the bumper, not the wheels.

44:38.200 --> 44:40.200
I'm sure you realise that.

44:41.320 --> 44:42.400
(CLATTER)

44:42.480 --> 44:43.720
Whoa!

44:43.800 --> 44:46.160
Hammond, you've put
my window through.

44:46.240 --> 44:47.800
Oh, there is a God!

44:47.880 --> 44:51.000
I'm gonna back up to amuse
myself looking at this.

44:51.080 --> 44:52.480
JAMES: Reverse!

44:52.560 --> 44:53.840
RICHARD: Yeah, but you've
become disconnected

44:53.920 --> 44:55.520
on your back bumper
on one side.

44:58.160 --> 45:00.920
Oh, God, now mine's died
and it's boiling.

45:01.000 --> 45:03.320
JAMES:
Whoa, that's proper boiling.

45:03.400 --> 45:07.840
RICHARD: My only option
was to try and keep some air
flowing through the radiator.

45:07.920 --> 45:09.920
So I set off once more.

45:15.520 --> 45:17.520
Errr...

45:21.640 --> 45:24.560
It's swimming through ash,
that's the problem.

45:26.280 --> 45:29.160
It's now getting hotter
than ever and I don't
like this edge.

45:33.480 --> 45:35.840
(BLEEP)
That shat me up a bit.

45:43.560 --> 45:47.440
Clarkson, how
much further is it to this
"No picture opportunity"?

45:47.520 --> 45:52.160
Not much further now. Only
a couple of... Oh, a bit.

45:53.320 --> 45:55.120
He doesn't know.

45:55.200 --> 45:58.840
JEREMY: But then I saw
exactly the sort of ridge

45:58.920 --> 46:02.640
condors use to keep aloft.

46:02.720 --> 46:06.160
To reach it,
though, we'd have to
turn off the track.

46:07.480 --> 46:10.480
Now let's show those two
what the Jeep can do.

46:13.080 --> 46:15.080
There you go, there you go.

46:16.800 --> 46:18.800
(STRAINING)

46:20.360 --> 46:23.360
JAMES:
No, I can't get up there.

46:23.440 --> 46:26.160
That simply doesn't work.

46:26.240 --> 46:28.240
It's like talcum powder.

46:36.200 --> 46:38.720
No. Stuck again.

46:40.880 --> 46:42.880
Come on. Come on, Jeep.

46:44.120 --> 46:46.120
Yes, you little beauty.

46:55.520 --> 46:57.520
JEREMY: Uhh.

47:02.640 --> 47:07.000
Um, I may have overreached
myself a little bit.

47:07.080 --> 47:08.440
RICHARD:
Oh, look at all the condors.

47:08.520 --> 47:11.160
I can see they're everywhere.

47:11.240 --> 47:14.120
It doesn't work.
Let's face it.

47:15.160 --> 47:18.080
I've had a brilliant idea.

47:18.160 --> 47:22.480
Let's just get off
this dusty bit
and set our hides up there.

47:22.560 --> 47:24.280
Yes.

47:28.720 --> 47:30.720
JEREMY:
So, we drove off the dust...

47:33.840 --> 47:37.200
...found a new
likely-looking spot,

47:37.280 --> 47:39.320
and when the clouds
had lifted,

47:39.400 --> 47:43.120
we set about getting ready
to do photography.

47:47.800 --> 47:52.680
The idea of the netting
is it stops the shine
on the windows.

47:52.760 --> 47:54.960
Very visible to animals.

47:55.040 --> 47:57.040
Oh.

47:58.320 --> 48:00.320
There was some
on this side as well.

48:03.440 --> 48:06.480
-Right, it's ready.
-You're going up in it?

48:06.560 --> 48:08.240
Well, why would you not?

48:08.320 --> 48:10.240
Well, I can see one reason.

48:10.320 --> 48:11.560
You see the maximum weight?

48:11.640 --> 48:13.600
159kg.

48:13.680 --> 48:15.840
-What's...?
-Well, you're not going
anywhere, are you?

48:15.920 --> 48:19.040
-Well, the camera
is quite heavy.
-No... OK, it's the camera.

48:20.040 --> 48:22.040
(WHIRRING)

48:24.160 --> 48:26.160
Bye!

48:30.280 --> 48:33.280
This is a lot higher than
it looked in the brochure.

48:33.360 --> 48:34.960
I wouldn't like that.

48:35.040 --> 48:37.040
(LAUGHS)
That's really horrible.

48:39.480 --> 48:42.400
-Keep going
till the end bit drops out.
-(LAUGHS)

48:42.480 --> 48:44.080
-Why don't you two...
-Yes?

48:44.160 --> 48:45.520
..get in your cars.

48:45.600 --> 48:46.720
-Yes?
-OK.

48:46.800 --> 48:49.560
And can I just reinforce
one thing?

48:49.640 --> 48:52.240
RICHARD: What?
-Silence is key.

48:52.320 --> 48:54.320
JAMES: Agreed.

49:05.160 --> 49:07.280
That ridge up there
looks promising.

49:07.360 --> 49:08.760
Right.

49:08.840 --> 49:10.920
(RATCHETTING)

49:11.000 --> 49:13.040
Where is it?

49:13.120 --> 49:15.640
No, no, no, back a bit, back.

49:15.720 --> 49:19.040
I can't go back. I'll have
to go all the way round.

49:19.120 --> 49:21.000
I can hear it from up here.

49:25.080 --> 49:27.120
Right, that one there, stop.

49:27.200 --> 49:29.200
Got it.

49:33.960 --> 49:35.960
RICHARD:
Think I'll make a coffee.
-(CLATTERING)

49:37.560 --> 49:39.240
Sorry.

49:39.320 --> 49:42.800
JEREMY: Then it was May's
turn to disturb the peace.

49:42.880 --> 49:44.880
(DUCK-LIKE
AMPLIFIED BIRD CRIES)

49:46.560 --> 49:47.840
JEREMY: What is that?

49:47.920 --> 49:49.520
It's a bird call.

49:49.600 --> 49:53.040
It's a duck!

49:53.120 --> 49:56.720
JEREMY: Moments later,
though, there was
an even worse noise.

49:57.840 --> 49:59.360
-(THUNDER)
RICHARD: Oh, God.

49:59.440 --> 50:00.920
JEREMY: Jesus!

50:01.000 --> 50:02.600
RICHARD: If only there was
something tall and metal

50:02.680 --> 50:04.280
that would attract
the lightning.

50:06.160 --> 50:10.560
JEREMY: Not wishing to be
fried, I quickly descended.

50:10.640 --> 50:13.600
And then we all tried to
outrun the storm...

50:16.240 --> 50:18.200
which didn't work.

50:18.280 --> 50:20.280
(THUNDER)

50:24.400 --> 50:27.240
JEREMY: Jesus Christ!

50:27.320 --> 50:30.480
We're 250 miles
from the equator,

50:30.560 --> 50:33.120
we're on a volcano
in a severe hailstorm.

50:38.120 --> 50:41.080
How much hail is there
in the sky?

50:41.160 --> 50:43.160
There's hail coming in now.

50:45.800 --> 50:48.880
It's bouncing in
through the back.

50:48.960 --> 50:50.960
RICHARD: Still, we got some
great condor photographs.

50:52.760 --> 50:55.360
Oh... (BLEEP)
...look at this now.

50:55.440 --> 50:58.040
JEREMY:
Life in the Jeep was hideous.

50:58.120 --> 51:00.120
Oh, God.

51:01.240 --> 51:04.320
Ah, ah... (BLEEP)

51:04.400 --> 51:07.560
Ice right down
the back of my neck.

51:07.640 --> 51:09.600
Oh... (BLEEP)

51:09.680 --> 51:11.840
I've just put all the ice
down the back of my seat.

51:11.920 --> 51:13.440
Oh, bollocks!

51:13.520 --> 51:15.840
Richard was very sympathetic.

51:15.920 --> 51:18.080
Oh, dear.

51:18.160 --> 51:20.160
Oh, that is a lot of snow.

51:21.720 --> 51:23.400
(LAUGHS)

51:23.480 --> 51:27.480
Oh, joy. Joyous moment.

51:29.920 --> 51:32.400
JEREMY: Mercifully, though,
the storm passed,

51:32.480 --> 51:38.400
so we drove down the rough
and icy mountain track,
long into the night.

51:42.240 --> 51:43.640
(BELL RINGS)

51:43.720 --> 51:46.080
And the next morning
woke for a rethink

51:46.160 --> 51:49.640
in a makeshift
camp on the edge of a town.

51:57.200 --> 51:59.800
(GROANS)

52:04.360 --> 52:06.360
(CAMERA SHUTTER)

52:07.880 --> 52:09.240
What are you doing?

52:09.320 --> 52:11.440
I told you condors
live down here.

52:11.520 --> 52:14.880
Living?
It was living up there
and it's had engine failure,

52:14.960 --> 52:16.360
and it's crashed here.

52:16.440 --> 52:18.160
Doesn't matter how
it got here. Fact is, it is

52:18.240 --> 52:20.760
and I've got the pictures of
it. That means we're done.

52:20.840 --> 52:22.640
-You can't put that...
-(CAMERA SHUTTER)

52:22.720 --> 52:25.360
...on an Amazon screen saver.

52:25.440 --> 52:26.720
Why not?

52:26.800 --> 52:30.040
-Well...
-(CREAKING AND THUD)

52:30.120 --> 52:32.200
It's lost quite a lot
of its majesty.

52:32.280 --> 52:35.480
But it's a condor, and that
means we're finished,
that's it. We're done.

52:35.560 --> 52:37.640
James,
I've got a condor shot.

52:37.720 --> 52:39.040
Have you?
Have you done it?

52:39.120 --> 52:41.520
That is the final one.
It's a condor, in camera,

52:41.600 --> 52:43.840
finished, out of here.

52:45.840 --> 52:47.240
JEREMY:
Hammond was wrong, though.

52:47.320 --> 52:50.200
We still had
one more animal to find.

52:50.280 --> 52:52.280
The one that didn't
make any sense.

52:53.320 --> 52:55.560
The hippopotamus.

52:55.640 --> 53:00.120
Right, listen, this is
obviously some kind of town.

53:00.200 --> 53:03.040
I am a journalist,
and a bloody good one.

53:04.360 --> 53:06.200
So why don't I pop into town

53:06.280 --> 53:09.560
and see if I can find out
anything about this
hippopotamus story?

53:11.720 --> 53:13.720
(BARKING)

53:21.720 --> 53:25.160
RICHARD:
My hide did not do well
on that drive last night.

53:29.520 --> 53:32.280
JEREMY: No, I can see that,
and neither did my camera.

53:32.360 --> 53:36.680
No, it's, um, fogged up, I
think, is the technical term.

53:36.760 --> 53:39.960
JAMES: My car actually
fell over in the night.

53:40.040 --> 53:42.200
I know nothing about it.

53:42.280 --> 53:45.680
JEREMY: Once we'd parked,
I set about doing journalism.

53:45.760 --> 53:47.640
(BARKING)

53:47.720 --> 53:49.840
This is like being back on
the Rotherham Advertiser.

53:49.920 --> 53:51.920
Except this is nothing
like Rotherham.

53:54.000 --> 53:56.240
-Buenos dias.
MAN: Buenos dias.

53:56.320 --> 53:58.320
Hippopotamus.

54:00.320 --> 54:01.640
Hippopotami?

54:01.720 --> 54:03.760
Gracias.

54:03.840 --> 54:06.320
Nobody knows, nobody knows.

54:06.400 --> 54:08.480
Having drawn
a journalistic blank...

54:08.560 --> 54:09.800
Excuse me.

54:09.880 --> 54:12.280
..I decided
to do art instead.

54:17.280 --> 54:18.640
Hippopotamus.

54:18.720 --> 54:21.280
-What?
-Hippopotamus.

54:21.360 --> 54:25.080
Yes. Where?

54:25.160 --> 54:27.320
(SPEAKS SPANISH)

54:27.400 --> 54:29.880
What's that? Got a
Spanish-speaking cameraman,
where is he?

54:29.960 --> 54:31.280
What's that mean?

54:31.360 --> 54:33.360
(EXCHANGE IN SPANISH)

54:36.120 --> 54:37.640
CAMERAMAN: They are here.

54:37.720 --> 54:40.080
-They are here?
-(REPLIES)

54:40.160 --> 54:42.400
-Where are they?
-(CAMERAMAN TRANSLATES)

54:42.480 --> 54:46.800
(EXCHANGE IN SPANISH)

54:46.880 --> 54:51.600
JEREMY:
Having got the information,
I went back to my colleagues.

54:52.600 --> 54:54.040
Any joy?

54:54.120 --> 54:55.560
More than.

54:55.640 --> 55:00.040
I have heard the most
astonishing story.

55:00.120 --> 55:03.000
Apparently there was
this guy in Colombia

55:03.080 --> 55:07.120
who had a business
exporting forest products
all around the world, OK?

55:07.200 --> 55:09.440
Really, really successful.
So successful,

55:09.520 --> 55:12.560
he bought himself
some pet hippopotamuses.

55:12.640 --> 55:15.280
-Who was he?
-Pablo someone or other.

55:15.360 --> 55:17.160
Anyway, the police shot him.

55:17.240 --> 55:19.880
-Why?
-I don't know.

55:19.960 --> 55:23.200
They shot him
and after he was dead,
his hippopotamuses escaped.

55:23.280 --> 55:26.680
Yeah?
And they've been living
in the wild and breeding.

55:26.760 --> 55:29.720
So there are hippopotamuses
here and they are wild

55:29.800 --> 55:31.600
and I know where they are

55:31.680 --> 55:34.600
and they're only 120km away.

55:34.680 --> 55:36.880
-Well, we're in.
-Let's do it.

55:36.960 --> 55:38.560
-Finish your coffees.
JAMES: That's excellent.

55:38.640 --> 55:40.080
RICHARD:
That is staggering news.

55:40.160 --> 55:41.840
The only thing is,
for this 120km,

55:41.920 --> 55:44.560
would either of you mind
if I modified my car?

55:44.640 --> 55:46.480
By unmodifying it.

55:52.320 --> 55:54.600
JEREMY: Having all
unmodified our cars,

55:54.680 --> 55:56.880
I decided
that before moving out,

55:56.960 --> 55:59.880
there was a small job to do.

55:59.960 --> 56:04.720
Right, I've borrowed
something from Hammond
to annoy May. (CLICKS TONGUE)

56:14.760 --> 56:16.760
â™ª LOS YETIS: Soy Un Hombre

56:27.200 --> 56:31.520
Seeing that little
New Labour Fiat Panda
with its Brexit sticker on.

56:31.600 --> 56:34.560
(LAUGHS)

56:34.640 --> 56:39.760
That is like putting an
I-heart-Mexico sticker on the
back of Donald Trump's Beast.

56:39.840 --> 56:41.840
I mean, his car, not...

56:45.040 --> 56:50.680
JEREMY: We were now
on the last 75 miles
of our 1300-mile trek

56:50.760 --> 56:56.160
through what had turned out
to be one of the world's
most incredible countries.

56:58.400 --> 57:03.320
If you were to combine Canada
and Russia and Australia,

57:03.400 --> 57:05.680
you still wouldn't have
the variety,

57:05.760 --> 57:09.040
in terms of terrain and
temperature and wildlife,

57:09.120 --> 57:11.960
that we've seen on this...

57:12.040 --> 57:15.040
absolutely epic journey.

57:46.160 --> 57:50.160
But of course,
we wouldn't have been
able to see any of that

57:50.240 --> 57:52.080
without our cars.

57:52.160 --> 57:54.160
â™ª LOS DUG DUG'S: Felicidad

58:05.440 --> 58:10.000
Let me just remind you
that this is a small,
49 horsepower,

58:10.080 --> 58:13.640
one-litre utility hatchback.

58:13.720 --> 58:16.480
It is a humble car.

58:16.560 --> 58:20.040
And yet that humility
is actually its strength.

58:20.120 --> 58:23.160
Because it's done everything
the other two cars have done.

58:23.240 --> 58:26.920
It's climbed the same
mountains, it's driven along
the same rutted tracks,

58:27.000 --> 58:29.880
it's forded
the same small rivers.

58:29.960 --> 58:32.080
It's absolutely brilliant.
I love it.

58:37.000 --> 58:39.360
On this trip, the camera
and production teams

58:39.440 --> 58:43.880
have lost six almost new
Toyota Land Cruisers.

58:45.400 --> 58:48.520
Hammond has lost
a half shaft.

58:48.600 --> 58:52.280
May's lost
most of his electrics
and a starter motor.

58:54.040 --> 58:56.000
But this... nothing.

58:56.080 --> 58:59.360
Nothing has gone wrong.

58:59.440 --> 59:02.240
It's taken everything that
Colombia could throw at it.

59:02.320 --> 59:04.920
Temperature extremes,
altitude extremes,

59:05.000 --> 59:06.440
roads like
you wouldn't believe

59:06.520 --> 59:09.000
and it's just gone,
"Yeah? What?"

59:10.960 --> 59:12.960
Yes, it's desperately
uncomfortable

59:13.040 --> 59:14.600
and if you hit
a pothole hard enough,

59:14.680 --> 59:18.080
it would put your spine
through the top
of your skull.

59:18.160 --> 59:20.920
But, and this is
more important,

59:21.000 --> 59:25.440
I liked it when we got here
and I like it even more now.

59:28.080 --> 59:30.080
It has a sturdy heart.

59:36.840 --> 59:41.160
I do realise
that James Bond doesn't
drive a monster truck.

59:41.240 --> 59:44.400
Nobody in a suit, in fact,
has ever driven
a monster truck.

59:44.480 --> 59:47.240
They're not... cool.

59:47.320 --> 59:52.200
You could argue,
as the other two have, that
they're moronic and stupid.

59:52.280 --> 59:55.000
Or you could argue
that they're fun...

59:55.080 --> 59:58.520
Cos that's what they are.
They're built
to make you smile.

59:58.600 --> 1:00:01.760
And what amazes me
is that even with the
modifications done to it,

1:00:01.840 --> 1:00:03.200
all of which
have made it worse...

1:00:03.280 --> 1:00:07.600
It's too tall, too wide,
too slow. It overheats.

1:00:07.680 --> 1:00:10.280
...still it's done everything
the other two cars have done,

1:00:10.360 --> 1:00:12.360
which makes it the best,

1:00:12.440 --> 1:00:14.440
easily, in my opinion.

1:00:15.480 --> 1:00:17.960
Oh, my car's gone again.

1:00:18.040 --> 1:00:20.000
My car has just died again.

1:00:20.080 --> 1:00:22.920
I'm pulling over.

1:00:23.000 --> 1:00:26.720
JEREMY: Had you just done
a piece to camera saying
what a great truck it was?

1:00:26.800 --> 1:00:28.800
RICHARD: I may have done.

1:00:31.280 --> 1:00:32.360
Yeah.

1:00:34.560 --> 1:00:37.720
JEREMY: Eventually the Trump
truck was back in business.

1:00:40.400 --> 1:00:44.080
And soon we were close
to our final destination.

1:00:48.600 --> 1:00:52.640
Right, this apparently
is the area where
the businessman lived.

1:00:52.720 --> 1:00:55.160
And if you go down
his escape road here...

1:00:55.240 --> 1:00:56.920
-His what?
-Escape road.

1:00:57.000 --> 1:00:59.760
He built it
in case the police came.

1:00:59.840 --> 1:01:01.200
And so he could get away.

1:01:01.280 --> 1:01:03.120
-It wasn't very good, then.
-No, it wasn't.

1:01:03.200 --> 1:01:07.760
Anyway, if you go down it,
there's a pool where
the hippos are now living.

1:01:08.760 --> 1:01:10.280
Target acquired.
Let's do it.

1:01:10.360 --> 1:01:12.040
JAMES: Let's do that.
-Hippos!

1:01:17.800 --> 1:01:20.120
So, a quick dash
down the escape route...

1:01:21.520 --> 1:01:24.160
to the water,
grab a shot of a hippo.

1:01:28.840 --> 1:01:30.880
Yes, viewers,
about a kilometre to go

1:01:30.960 --> 1:01:34.080
and I haven't been run over
by a monster truck.

1:01:34.160 --> 1:01:35.600
(REVVING)

1:01:35.680 --> 1:01:37.680
I'm absolutely delighted.

1:01:39.240 --> 1:01:40.800
Hammond,
I can only see you behind me.

1:01:40.880 --> 1:01:42.880
Can you see Clarkson
behind you?

1:01:44.080 --> 1:01:46.760
No. Just looking for him.

1:01:46.840 --> 1:01:51.640
RICHARD: At that moment,
though, we were distracted by
what lay in front of us.

1:01:56.680 --> 1:01:58.840
That is a pond!

1:01:58.920 --> 1:02:01.080
That's a pond.

1:02:01.160 --> 1:02:03.160
JAMES: Yes.

1:02:05.480 --> 1:02:07.160
-We're in with a shout here.
-What?

1:02:07.240 --> 1:02:09.200
Well, that looks like a hippo
sort of pond, doesn't it?

1:02:09.280 --> 1:02:11.560
Who put that..
Did you put that on my car?

1:02:11.640 --> 1:02:13.680
-What?
-That sticker?

1:02:13.760 --> 1:02:15.360
No, I thought you did
when you did your mods.

1:02:15.440 --> 1:02:17.560
-Don't be ridiculous.
-Well, I was surprised.

1:02:17.640 --> 1:02:19.280
It's a strong statement
for you but...

1:02:19.360 --> 1:02:21.320
You did that at that
fuel stop, didn't you?

1:02:21.400 --> 1:02:23.800
-No, it's been there since
your mods went on, mate.
-No, it hasn't.

1:02:23.880 --> 1:02:27.280
You shout it loud and proud.
I wouldn't let
your friends see it.

1:02:27.360 --> 1:02:29.600
Anyway, important business
to be done.

1:02:31.360 --> 1:02:32.800
RICHARD:
Rather than wait for Jeremy,

1:02:32.880 --> 1:02:34.240
we decided to be ready

1:02:34.320 --> 1:02:36.880
in case our
final target appeared.

1:02:56.600 --> 1:02:58.600
(BUBBLING)

1:03:00.000 --> 1:03:02.000
Hammond...

1:03:09.560 --> 1:03:11.560
He-he-he.

1:03:14.040 --> 1:03:16.880
Martha Hussein,
you are in my sights.

1:03:24.040 --> 1:03:26.040
Look at his big fat face.

1:03:35.120 --> 1:03:37.120
JAMES: Yes!

1:03:38.720 --> 1:03:41.520
-Well, that's it.
-That's tremendous.

1:03:41.600 --> 1:03:43.080
(CHUCKLING)

1:03:43.160 --> 1:03:45.640
Hippopotamus!

1:03:45.720 --> 1:03:47.320
Photos of a hippo.

1:03:47.400 --> 1:03:49.880
-Congratulations.
-Well done, us.

1:03:49.960 --> 1:03:53.040
I say we've done it.
We've done it. Where's...

1:03:53.120 --> 1:03:54.840
I know, I've been
worrying about that.

1:03:54.920 --> 1:03:56.440
Well, if it gets here,

1:03:56.520 --> 1:03:58.080
you realise that'll be
the first time

1:03:58.160 --> 1:03:59.600
any car
on any of these trips

1:03:59.680 --> 1:04:02.040
has ever got to the end
without a single fault.

1:04:02.120 --> 1:04:03.560
Nothing's gone wrong with it.

1:04:03.640 --> 1:04:05.280
That's about the only time
that's ever happened.

1:04:05.360 --> 1:04:07.640
-The car, get to the end,
it hasn't broken at all.
-You're right.

1:04:07.720 --> 1:04:09.720
That's a record.

1:04:11.520 --> 1:04:13.800
You don't think he fell off
that little scary bridgy bit?

1:04:13.880 --> 1:04:15.880
I don't know.

1:04:15.960 --> 1:04:18.680
He overcooked it
because it's near the end.
And tried to do some...

1:04:18.760 --> 1:04:21.040
-Hang on a minute,
is that...?
-It is.

1:04:21.120 --> 1:04:26.320
Oh, brief moment of
elation followed by
plummeting depression.

1:04:26.400 --> 1:04:28.120
(JAMES LAUGHS)

1:04:29.800 --> 1:04:31.640
-Where have you been?
-Welcome.

1:04:31.720 --> 1:04:33.560
I've been mending my camera.

1:04:33.640 --> 1:04:35.520
-You don't need it.
-What?

1:04:35.600 --> 1:04:37.880
We've done it, mate.
We've got shots of a hippo.
It is done.

1:04:37.960 --> 1:04:40.120
-We've finished.
We've done it.
-Behold the hippo.

1:04:40.200 --> 1:04:41.640
We got shots
of a hippo just then.

1:04:41.720 --> 1:04:43.360
Came out
a couple of minutes ago.

1:04:43.440 --> 1:04:45.360
-So that's the end?
-That is the end.
-Job done.

1:04:45.440 --> 1:04:48.600
And we've got through the
whole programme without
once mentioning cocaine.

1:04:48.680 --> 1:04:50.480
Oh.

1:04:50.560 --> 1:04:53.080
James, we said
before we came out here,

1:04:53.160 --> 1:04:54.720
we weren't going to use
the c-word.

1:04:54.800 --> 1:04:57.000
We were going to be
the first people ever

1:04:57.080 --> 1:04:59.680
to go to Colombia
and not talk that.

1:04:59.760 --> 1:05:00.840
Sorry.

1:05:00.920 --> 1:05:03.440
It just slipped out.

1:05:03.520 --> 1:05:05.240
And on that terrible
disappointment,
it's time to end.

1:05:05.320 --> 1:05:07.920
We hope you enjoy looking at
the photographs we've taken.

1:05:08.000 --> 1:05:10.400
-They won't.
-Well, some of them
are quite good.

1:05:10.480 --> 1:05:12.360
-Well, one or two of them
are good.
-No.

1:05:12.440 --> 1:05:14.800
Well, whatever.
We'll see you very soon.

1:05:14.880 --> 1:05:16.120
Goodbye.

